lso shows the various ways these artists strategically demoted regionalism in favor of a new modernist voice that transcended the traditions of the nation-state and contributed to a nascent globalization of the art world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArts audiencesxHistoryy20th century. 0aConcrete art - Social aspects - Latin America - History - 20th century. 0aConcrete artxSocial aspectszLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aConcrete artzLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aAbstract Art.  aArt History.  aCritical Theory.  aCultural politics.  aLatin America.  aLiterary theory.  aMedia.  aModernism.  aSemiotics.  aSpectatorship.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226394008423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226394008/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles